Part I - Prosper Loan Data¶

by Estitxu Larralde Erasun¶

Introduction¶

As per their website, Prosper is a peer-to-peer lending marketplace in the United States. It was founded in 2005.

The dataset includes 113 937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, interest rate, loan status and many more.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 113937 rows or loans and 81 columns or features.

After creating a copy of the dataset to prevent any modification of the original dataset, I filtered only the columns I was interested in for this analysis. Then I did some data wrangling to drop the null values, the duplicated rows and change the format of some columns. I also modified some values of the EmploymentStatus column to group any status that belonged into Employed.

After all the wrangling, there are 49731 observations (rows) and 11 features (columns)

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm interested in the loan status and the BorrowerAPR (annual interest rate). I'd like to find out the correlation between the different variables and the result of the loan (is it successful or not? i.e. was it reimboursed?). Regarding the BorrowerAPR I'd like to see if there is correlation of some variables with obtaining a low interest rate.

LoanStatus column contains categorical data (format in the dataset is not correct): Completed, FinalPaymentInProgress, Past Due (1-15 days), Past Due (16-30 days), Past Due (31-60 days), Past Due (61-90 days), Past Due (91-120 days), Past Due (>120 days), Chargedoff, Defaulted.

As Cancelled loans have never been created, they can be dropped, as well as Current status loans, because we don't know the outcome.

BorrowerAPR is a float number (float data type) representing the interest rate obtained by the borrower for their loan.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think the 'stated monthly income', the 'employment status' and the 'revolving credit balance' could have some correlation with the status of the loans.

I would like to measure also the features that seem to weigh on the APR of the borrower of each loan. I think similar features as the ones mentioned just above could have some correlation with the obtained APR. On the other hand, other features as Term (usually loans with fewer instalments get a lower interest rate) could have some influence, too.

In the Matter of Prosper Marketplace, Inc.¶

On November 24, the Commission issued an Order Instituting Administrative Proceedings Pursuant to Section 8A of the Securities Act of 1933, Making Findings and Imposing a Cease and Desist Order (Order) against Prosper Marketplace, Inc. (Prosper). The Order finds that Prosper violated Sections 5(a) and (c) of the Securities Act of 1933 during the period January 1, 2006 through October 14, 2008, by engaging in the unregistered offering of securities via Prosper's online lending platform. Prosper offers loans in a double-blind, auction-like process wherein multiple lenders bid to fund loans to borrowers. Since the inception of its platform in January 2006, Prosper has initiated approximately $174 million in loans.

Source: https://www.sec.gov/news/digest/2008/dig112408.htm

End of April 2009 the California Department of Corporations gave the go-ahead to operate again to Prosper but activity slowed down quite a bit due to stricter rules for borrowers:

Prosper's relaunched version will have slightly new rules. Borrowers will have to have credit scores above 640 to request a loan now, for example.

Source: https://money.cnn.com/2009/04/28/technology/hempel_prosper.fortune/?section=money_technology

Conclusions¶

I started by cleaning and tidying up the dataset by dropping null values, duplicates and modifying the format of some features.

I chose the two features that interested me most : LoanStatus and BorrowerAPR (annual interest rate of the loans). I thought about which features could have some correlation with my two features of interest : 'stated monthly income', 'employment status' and the 'revolving credit balance'.

Then I started the exploratory analysis by univariate visualization. The most interesting findings at that level were that:

  • over 28% of loans in the sample were not paid back, i.e. the risk for lenders is quite high as compared to other financial products.
  • BorrowerAPR, or annual interest rate had a peak at 0.355-0.36, which is a very high interest rate for a loan.
  • Count of loans decreased and even stopped during a few months between October 2008 and May 2009. The reason was SEC's intervention. Since then the rules to grant loans got more strict. Therefore the count of loans from July 2009 onwards decreased and didn't get back to previous level. The ratio between Unsuccessful (not paid back to lenders) and Succesful (paid back) also decreased.
  • Majority of borrowers were employed, either by a company or self-employed
  • A few numerical features were really skewed to the right: RevolvingCreditBalance, StatedMonthlyIncome and LoanOriginalAmount. I had to limit the range of values to visualize them and sometimes I used a log scale, too.

During the bivariate visualizations, I started doing a correlation matrix between BorrowerAPR and numerical features (Term, IsBorrowerHomeowner, Investors, LoanOriginalAmount, RevolvingCreditBalance and StatedMonthlyIncome). I found no correlation between most of them and BorrowerAPR or LoanStatus feature. Nevertheless, I found out that :

  • There is quite a strong negative correlation between the two features of interest, i.e. LoanStatus and BorrowerAPR. Succesful loans got over all a lower average BorrowerAPR.
  • There is some positive correlation between LoanStatus and LoanOriginal Amount: there are proportionally more loans with a bigger amount among unsuccessful loans, eventhough average loan amount for either succesful and unsuccesful loans is very similar.
  • There is some positive correlation between StatedMonthlyIncome and LoanStatus. Borrowers of successful loans stated in average about 1000USD of monthly income more (about 5500USD) than those of unsuccesful loans (4500USD).
  • There is some correlation between Employed and Retired values of EmploymentStatus and LoanStatus. Indeed, borrowers from these two categories were proportionnaly more succesful paying back the loans than borrowers in categories Unemployed and Other.
  • Similarly,employed or retired borrowers got a lower average annual interest rate (BorrowerAPR) than the other two categories.

I used the multivariate visualization to deepen the analysis of correlated features. I first tried to visualize the correlation between BorrowerAPR, LoanStatus and Employment Status:

  • The visualization helped to see the correlation between the three figures. Both loan status and employment status are correlated to the borrower APR. Two categories of employment status (employed and retired) got lower average interest rate than the rest of the employment categories. Even in the case of loans that got unsuccesful for employed and retired borrowers, the average annual interest rate was lower than for succesful loans of unemployed and other category borrowers.

I wanted to see another side of the borrowerAPR vs. loanstatus correlation by adding LoanOriginalAmount in a multivariate visualization. I could observe that:

  • Most loans original amount is below 15000USD.
  • The ratio between unsuccesful and succesful loans increases as the loan original amount does, but the BorrowerAPR is in average lower when the loan original amount increases. This means that unsuccesful loans concentrate around small loan original amounts at a higher average APR rate than succesful loans

I also visualized investors against loan original amount and loan status to deepen in the correlation between investors and loan original amount:

  • The positive correlation between these two figures was easy to identify in the visualization.
  • As for the loan status, there seemed to be an increasing ratio of unsuccesful/succesful loans as the amount of the loan increased. Nevertheless, there seemed to be no correlation between the number of investors and the loan status.
